(
 '# Repack'
 ''
 ']Repack is used to clean up and optimise Git''s internal storage by consolidating loose objects into packfiles.'
 ''
 'Over time, as you commit, Git stores objects (blobs, trees, commits) as individual files. That gets inefficient.'
 ''
 'This is what ]Repack does:\\'
 '* Compresses those loose objects into a single (or few) .pack file(s)'
 '* Removes the original loose objects (unless you tell it not to)'
 '* Optionally removes old packfiles and replaces them with a new one'
 ''
 ']Repack uses 250 as default values for both "depth" and "window", but check the corresponding options.'
 ''
 ']Repack always uses the following flags:'
 ''
 '* -a --- Repack all objects, not just loose ones'
 '* -d --- Delete redundant packs after the new one is written'
 '* -f --- Force recompression even for objects already in packs'
 ''
 '-depth=         Use this to override the Git default which is 50'
 '-window=        Use this to override the Git default which is 10 '
)
